# The Cat

> iOS app — Jeremie Berduck

## Overview

A native iOS app built as part of the Egeniq iOS code assessment.

The app fetches a list of cat breeds from TheCatAPI and displays them in a paginated list with one image per breed. Each entry shows name, origin, life span, and temperament. A detail screen adds the cat information, and a Swift Charts life span bar chart.

API: `GET https://api.thecatapi.com/v1/breeds?page=0&limit=12`
Auth: `x-api-key` request header
Time budget: 3 hours

---

## Architecture: MVVM

**Why MVVM?** Views stay declarative; all state and business logic lives in the ViewModel where it can be unit-tested without a UI. SwiftUI's data-flow model maps naturally onto it.

```
The Cat/
├── The_CatApp.swift              # @main entry — creates the window
├── ContentView.swift             # Root view — owns the ViewModel instance
├── Configuration/
│   ├── Config.xcconfig           # Injects API key at build time (git-ignored)
│   └── Configuration.swift       # Type-safe Bundle accessor for the key
├── Models/
│   └── Breed.swift               # Data model
├── Networking/
│   ├── APIClientProtocol.swift   # Abstraction seam for testing
│   ├── CatAPIClient.swift        # Concrete URLSession implementation
│   └── APIError.swift            # Typed error enum
├── ViewModels/
│   └── BreedListViewModel.swift  # All state + pagination logic
└── Views/
    ├── BreedListView.swift        # Paginated list + pull-to-refresh
    ├── BreedRowView.swift         # Single list row (thumbnail + metadata)
    └── BreedDetailView.swift      # Full detail screen with chart
```

---

## File-by-file

### App Shell

**`The_CatApp.swift`** — `@main` entry point.

**`ContentView.swift`** — The single place where `BreedListViewModel` is instantiated with the real `CatAPIClient`. Owns the state for the whole session. Kept separate from `The_CatApp` so it can be previewed and tested independently.

---

### Configuration

**`Config.xcconfig`** — Build configuration file that defines `CAT_API_KEY`. Referenced by `Info.plist` as `$(CAT_API_KEY)`. **Never commit a real key here** — add this file to `.gitignore`.

**`Configuration.swift`** — Reads values from `Bundle.main.infoDictionary` at runtime. Throws a typed `missingKey` error if a key is absent, so misconfiguration fails loudly instead of silently using an empty string.

---

### Models

**`Breed.swift`** — `Decodable` + `Identifiable` + `Equatable` struct. Maps snake_case JSON keys (`life_span`, `reference_image_id`) to camelCase Swift properties via `CodingKeys`. Computes `imageURL` from `referenceImageId` so callers never construct CDN URLs themselves. Includes a `static let preview` instance for SwiftUI `#Preview` blocks.

---

### Networking

**`APIClientProtocol.swift`** — Single-method protocol: `fetchBreeds(page:) async throws -> [Breed]`. The entire networking contract in one line. Exists solely so `BreedListViewModel` can accept a mock in tests without importing URLSession or touching the network.

**`CatAPIClient.swift`** — Concrete implementation. Builds the URL with `URLComponents` (no string interpolation on query params), injects the API key as the `x-api-key` header, and maps HTTP status codes to `APIError` cases before decoding. Page size is 12 (as it was in the requirements example, but can of course be adjusted) — hardcoded to match the ViewModel's pagination sentinel.

**`APIError.swift`** — `Equatable` error enum with five cases: `invalidURL`, `unauthorized`, `serverError(Int)`, `decodingError`, `unknown`. `Equatable` conformance lets tests assert the exact error without pattern-matching.

---

### ViewModel

**`BreedListViewModel.swift`** — Marked `@Observable` (Swift Observation framework, no Combine) and `@MainActor` (all UI state mutations on the main thread by default). Owns three public properties: `breeds`, `isLoading`, `errorMessage`.

Pagination works by tracking `currentPage` and `hasMorePages`. After each successful fetch, `hasMorePages` is set to `false` when the response contains fewer than 12 items — the view uses `.onAppear` on the last row to trigger the next page load. `refresh()` resets all state and re-fetches from page 0.

Dependency injection via constructor: `init(apiClient: APIClientProtocol)`. Production code passes `CatAPIClient()`; tests pass `MockAPIClient`.

---

### Views

**`BreedListView.swift`** — `NavigationStack` with a `List`. Handles three states: initial loading spinner (empty + `isLoading`), error via `ContentUnavailableView` (empty + `errorMessage`), and the populated list. Pagination trigger: `.onAppear` on the last visible row fires `loadBreeds()`. Inline loading indicator via `.safeAreaInset`. Errors while paginating appear as a dismissable capsule overlay so existing content stays visible.

**`BreedRowView.swift`** — Thumbnail (60×60, rounded) + breed name + origin/life-span subtitle. `AsyncImage` with a `pawprint` SF Symbol fallback for missing or failed images.

**`BreedDetailView.swift`** — Hero image (300pt tall, `scaledToFill`). Temperament string is split on commas into individual chip badges. Life span is parsed into `(min, max)` integers and rendered as a two-bar Swift Charts `BarMark` chart (scale fixed at 0–25 years). Falls back to plain text if the string can't be parsed.

---

## Key Design Decisions

| Concern | Choice | Why |
|---|---|---|
| State management | `@Observable` | No Combine; native SwiftUI integration in iOS 17+ |
| Async | `async/await` | First-class Swift concurrency, simpler than Combine pipelines |
| Networking | `URLSession` | No third-party dependency needed for one endpoint |
| Image loading | `AsyncImage` | Built-in, sufficient for this scale |
| Data viz | `Swift Charts BarMark` | Native; renders life span min/max at a glance |
| API key | xcconfig → Info.plist → Bundle | Keeps secrets out of source files |
| Testability | Protocol + constructor injection | Swap real client for mock in one line |
| Navigation | `NavigationStack` | SwiftUI-native, no `UINavigationController` bridging |

---

## Setup

Requirements: **Xcode 16+**, **iOS 17+**

```bash
git clone <repo-url>
open "The Cat/The Cat.xcodeproj"
```

The `Config.xcconfig` file should be git-ignored, but it is not for the purpose of the exercise. You can update it at `The Cat/The Cat/Configuration/Config.xcconfig`:

```
CAT_API_KEY = your_key_here
```

Build and run. The `Info.plist` picks up `$(CAT_API_KEY)` automatically.

---

## Testing

Unit tests use the **Swift Testing** framework (`@Suite`, `@Test`, `#expect`). UI tests use **XCUIAutomation**.

Run: `⌘U` in Xcode.

### What's tested

`MockAPIClient` implements `APIClientProtocol` and holds a `Result<[Breed], Error>` that tests set directly — no network calls ever made.

| Category | Tests |
|---|---|
| Happy path | Breeds array populated; `isLoading` cleared after success |
| Errors | Network error, server 500, timeout, decoding failure, 401 unauthorized |
| Edge cases | Empty response stops pagination; error message mentions "API key" on 401 |
| Pagination | Second call appends; no third call issued when `hasMorePages` is false |
| Resilience | `refresh()` after failure resets state and reloads successfully |

---

### AI Assistance

I've manually created all the structure I wanted to have for this project. Then I used AI for connecting things together, explaining clearly what was the expected result.

Test stubs and mock scaffolding were partially generated by AI. Each generated test was manually verified to assert the **right thing** — not just that it compiles and passes. Pay particular attention to async timing: AI-generated tests sometimes miss `await` on the act step or assert before state has settled.

